## Code nodes

Use Code nodes when built-in nodes cannot express the logic cleanly.

### Rules

| Rule | Detail |
|------|--------|
| Thin Code | Map `$input.all()` ↔ `lib/` functions; return `[{ json: ... }]` |
| Mode | Prefer **Run Once for All Items** or **Run Once for Each Item** deliberately — document choice |
| No secrets in code | Read from credentials or env via n8n patterns — not hardcoded |
| Return shape | Always return array of `{ json: {...} }` (and `binary` if needed) |
| Errors | `throw new Error('clear message')` or custom node `NodeOperationError` — no catch-and-ignore |
| Size | Under ~30 lines per Code node; extract helpers |
| Require path | Document how Code resolves `lib/` (absolute path, `NODE_PATH`, or package) |

```javascript
// Thin Code node — logic in lib/
const { normalizeRecord } = require('/path/to/lib/normalize');
const items = $input.all();
return items.map((item) => ({
  json: normalizeRecord(item.json),
}));
```

### When to escalate to a custom node

- Logic reused across many workflows or teams
- Needs credential test, dynamic properties, or resource routing
- Complex API pagination / listing patterns
- You want jest tests against `INodeType.execute()` with n8n mocks

See [[N8N-CODEBASE-DOCUMENTATION#Custom node / package notes]].

